<li><h3>Mirage: 2D Source Localization Using Microphone Pair Augmentation with Echoes</h3>
<p>Di Carlo, Diego and Deleforge, Antoine and Bertin, Nancy<br />
   <i></i><br />
   2019</p>

<button onclick="showTextInBoxBelow('DiCarlo2019-bibtex')">BibTex</button>


<button onclick="showTextInBoxBelow('DiCarlo2019-abstract')">Abstract</button>



<button onclick="openTab('https://github.com/Chutlhu/MIRAGE')">
    <font color="#268bd2" style="text-decoration: underline">[Code]</font>
</button>



<button onclick="openTab('https://arxiv.org/abs/' + '1906.08968')">
    <font color="#268bd2" style="text-decoration: underline">[arXiv]</font>
</button>




<button onclick="openTab('http://hal.inria.fr/' + 'hal-01909531')">
    <font color="#268bd2" style="text-decoration: underline">[HAL]</font>
</button>



<button onclick="openTab('http://doi.org/' + '10.1109/ICASSP.2019.8683534')">
    <font color="#268bd2" style="text-decoration: underline">[DOI]</font>
</button>


<div id="DiCarlo2019-bibtex" style="display:none;">
    <div class="highlight">
        <code>
        @inproceedings{DiCarlo2019,
  arxiv = {1906.08968},
  author = {Di Carlo, Diego and Deleforge, Antoine and Bertin, Nancy},
  booktitle = {IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP)},
  doi = {10.1109/ICASSP.2019.8683534},
  keywords = {Image Microphones,Sound Source Localization,Supervised Learning,TDOA Estimation},
  pages = {775--779},
  title = ,
  volume = {2019-May},
  year = {2019},
  url = {https://github.com/Chutlhu/MIRAGE},
  hal_id = {hal-01909531}
}

        </code>
    </div>
</div>

<div id="DiCarlo2019-abstract" style="display:none;">
        <div class="highlight">
            <code><i>
                It is commonly observed that acoustic echoes hurt performance of sound source localization (SSL) methods.
  We introduce the concept of microphone array augmentation with echoes (MIRAGE) and show how estimation of early-echo  characteristics can in fact benefit SSL.
  We propose a learningbased scheme for echo estimation combined with a physicsbased scheme for echo aggregation. 
  In a simple scenario involving 2 microphones close to a reflective surface and one source,
  we show using simulated data that the proposed approach performs similarly to a correlation-based method 
  in azimuth estimation while retrieving elevation as well from 2 microphones only, an impossible task in anechoic settings.</i>
            </code>
        </div>
</div>

